'''Eugène Murangwa''' (born 9 November 1975) is a former Rwandan international football player. His playing position was a goalkeeper.

In 1997, following an international match for Rwanda in Tunisia, he sought asylum and emigrated to the [[United Kingdom]] via [[Belgium]] following the [[Rwandan Genocide]].<ref>{{cite web|title=‘Zuzu, a person who tortured, raped and murdered many Tutsis, became Eric’s saviour not once, but twice. Why? Zuzu’s passion was Rayon Sports.’|url=http://www.hmd.org.uk/resources/stories/hmd-2015-eric-eugene-murangwa|publisher=HMD.org.uk|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> During the Genocide he lost 35 members of his family.

In 2010, he founded ''Football for Hope, Peace & Unity''.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the founder|url=http://www.fhpuenterprise.org/about-us/about-the-founder/|publisher=fhpuenterprise.org|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>

==International career==

He was involved in Rwanda's [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying campaign and played in a game versus [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>{{FIFA player|157511}}</ref>

